@NODE INFO "Introduction"

 FinalWriter 97 lacks a facility to automatically number chapters.  This  macro
 provides  a way to do semi-automatic numbering of chapters in an easy way. The
 titles are recognized through their style sheet.

@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "Installation"

 Simply copy the macro to your FWMacros directory. You can  use  the  Installer
 script for this:

    @{"Start installation" SYSTEM "Installer FinalChapters.install APPNAME FinalChapters MINUSER EXPERT NOPRETEND NOLOG NOPRINTER"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE USAGE "Usage"

 To use FinalChapters, you have to use style sheets called "TOC1", "TOC2"  etc.
 for  the titles (TOC stands for "Table of Contents"). Unfortunately, it is not
 possible for a macro to read the style sheet definitions, that's why the style
 sheets  must  have  these  specific  names to recognize the level of TOC entry
 generated by the style  sheet.  You  can  simply  change  the  names  of  your
 favourite style sheets accordingly.

 You should type your document as normal, but without using any chapter numbers
 by  yourself.  When your document's structure is complete (or you when want to
 print it), run FinalChapters to add the numbers. If the chapters  are  already
 numbered,  FinalChapter  will replace the existing numbers (this will not work
 if letters are used for the numbering, see below), so you  can  run  it  again
 later  to  update  the numbers if you made any changes. (If one of your titles
 should start with a number, precede it with a space to prevent the number from
 being deleted by FinalChapters).

 FinalChapters will first ask you to save your document  (as  it  will  perform
 possibly irreversible modifications).

 You will then be asked for the number of the first chapter (that is the  first
 top-level  TOC entry). Usually you would enter one of 1, A, or a. You may also
 start with higher numbers (e.g.  if  you  want  continuous  numbering  through
 different  sections  or  documents). You also may specify arbitrary characters
 before  or  after  the  number.  These  will  be  added  to   each   footnote.
 (FinalChapters will look for the first letter, or number starting from the end
 of what you entered to determine what system is to be used.)

 Uppercase letters are conventionally used for appendices and  decimal  numbers
 for other chapters. The different levels are separated by dots (".").

 E.g. You could type (5). In this case FinalChapters would generate the chapter
 numbers (5), (5.1), (5.2), ..., (6), (6.1), etc.

 FinalChapters then searches the main text section as well as all  text  frames
 for the style sheets and adds increasing numbers where appropriate.

 During this process, if a place is encountered where a level of TOC is skipped
 (e.g.  a  subsection  name  follows a chapter name without any section name in
 between) you are asked whether to accept this mistake or to correct it.

 When the job is done, FinalChapters will report on how  many  references  were
 found and whether there were any problems.
@ENDNODE
